    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener><placeName>Down Farnborough Kent</placeName>
                    <date>June 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.—</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental"><hi rend="underline">Private</hi></seg>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>It may appear ridiculous or not very credible, but in simple truth I am not equal to taking the chair of the Nat. Hist. Section, in Liverpool, where I hope to attend.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Very little fatigue, or excitement or anxiety (of which I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have plenty) almost invariably brings on so much swimming of the head, nausea, &amp; other symptoms, that the effort of sitting 2 or 3 (or even less) in a public chair would be quite intolerable to me.—</p>
<p>I assure you I feel to the full the honour of being asked to act as President to a section of the Brit. Association; &amp; for this honour &amp; others, I am (as I believe) indebted to you.— If you have occasion to make any excuse for me to others, be so kind as to make a general one on the score of health.—</p>
<p>Pray believe me, | Yours sincerely &amp; obliged | Charles Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> Colonel Sabine | &amp;c &amp;c &amp;c</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Sabine was general secretary of the British Association for the Advancement of Science in 1854.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In the event, CD did not attend the meeting in Liverpool in September 1854, perhaps because of the pressure of reading proofs for the Cirripedia volumes. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_259.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Hutton Balfour</ref> was president of section D (zoology and botany, including physiology).</note>
        </div>        
            
